      <section>
        <h2>A Brief History</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <h4>2000 - <a href='http://alistapart.com/article/dao' target='_blank'>A Dao of Web Design</a> <em>John Alsopp</em></h3>
            <p>"The web’s greatest strength, I believe, is often seen as a limitation, as a defect. It is the nature of the web to be flexible, and it should be our role as designers and developers to embrace this flexibility, and produce pages which, by being flexible, are accessible to all."</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <h4>2010 - <a href='http://alistapart.com/article/responsive-web-design' target='_blank'>Responsive Web Design</a> <em>Ethan Marcotte</em></h3>
            <p>"Can we really continue to commit to supporting each new user agent with its own bespoke experience? At some point, this starts to feel like a zero sum game. But how can we—and our designs—adapt?"</p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <h4>2013 - <a href='http://implementingresponsivedesign.com/' target='_blank'>Implementing Responsive Design</a> <em>Tim Kadlec</em></h3>
            <p>"What happens when refridgerators are connected to the internet? Will we then attempt to create a website targeted at refridgerators?"</p>
          </li>
          <li><strong>2014</strong> - Google adds "mobile-friendly" label to mobile search results</li>
          <li><strong>2016</strong> - Google says 85% of all pages in the mobile search results are now mobile-friendly, removes label</li>
        </ul>
